ce:section.ce:para:
The element analysis (detected before introducing NaOH) results shown in Table 1
                      indicate that the carbon contents of both GQDs and GO are higher than that of CA, implying that CA should be carbonized in some degree during the pyrolysis. Furthermore, the higher carbon content of GO suggests that the GO has higher carbonization degree than the GQDs. The XRD patterns of both GQDs and GO show a wide (002) peak around 0.34nm (Fig. 2
                     ), suggesting that carbonizing CA would produce graphite structures. FTIR was used to characterize the obtained GQDs and GO (Fig. 3
                     ). Both the GQDs and GO exhibit absorption of carboxyl group and hydroxyl group, showing that both of these two nanomaterials contain -COOH groups. Additionally, the GQDs show absorption of stretching vibration C–H at 2950cm−1 and stretching vibration of C–H in the range of below 1350cm−1, suggesting that the GQDs contain some incompletely carbonized CA. Contrarily, the GO exhibits nearly no absorption of C–H, implying that the CA sample has been carbonized completely. Furthermore, the C–OH group (stretching vibration at 1115cm−1) in the GO has been changed to the C–O–C group (stretching vibration at 1012cm−1) in the. It should be noted that no characteristic absorption bands of aromatic compound (stretching vibration of C–H in aromatic rings around 3000–3100cm−1, skeletal vibration of aromatic rings around 1450–1650cm−1) are included in these FTIR spectra, suggesting that no any aromatic compound is contained in the obtained CQDs and GO. The AFM result indicates that the GQDs (Fig. 4
                     a) are mostly nanosheets of ∼15nm in size, whose height is mostly distributed in the range of 0.5–2.0nm (1.4nm average height). Although high quality TEM images are difficult to be obtained due to the low electro contrast between the GQDs and the carbon coated TEM grids, some nanosheets of ∼15nm in size can still be observed (Fig. 4b). Both AFM (Fig. 4c) and TEM (Fig. 4d) results indicate that the GO are mostly sheets of much larger size (hundreds of nanometers). The height of the obtained GO is ∼1nm, which is the typical height of GO. On the basis of above mentioned XRD, FIRT, AFM, and TEM results, it follows that both GQD and GO may contain single graphite layer. The GQDs have larger height than the GO mostly due to the incompletely carbonized CA existing at their surface.

Both solutions of GQDs and GO emit blue light (460nm) when excited with 365nm UV beam (see Fig. 5
                      and Fig. 6
                     ). As well known, owing to the lack of a bandgap the possibility of observing luminescence of graphene seems highly unlikely [20]. However, considerable research results indicate that GO can emit near-infrared, visible and ultraviolet PL [6]. Although the exact mechanisms responsible for PL in GO remain to be elucidated, it is believed to be related to the sp3 matrix. The blue PL of GO was proposed to be produced by the ordered sp2 clusters with sizes of about 1nm isolated within the sp3 C–O matrix [5]. As mentioned above, both the obtained GQDs and GO contain abundant sp2 structures and oxygen-containing functional groups, thus it is reasonable to believe that the GQDs and GO should share the same luminescence origin of other luminescent GO. However, except for giving blue light emission under the excitation by 365nm UV light, there are some significant differences in optical properties between the GQDs and the GO. First of all, the emission wavelength of GQDs is nearly excitation-independent, with the maximum excitation wavelength and the maximum emission wavelength at 362 and 460nm, respectively (Fig. 5). The excitation-independent emission of the GQDs implies that both the size and the surface state of those sp2 clusters contained in GQDs should be uniform. On the contrary, the maximum emission wavelength of GO is substantially dependent on the excitation wavelength, shifts from 450 to 542nm when the excitation wavelength is increased gradually from 300 to 480nm (Fig. 6). Apparently, the broad and excitation-dependent emission of GO is similar to that of most CLNMs, which reflects effects from both sp2 of different size and different emission sites of each sp2 clusters [21,22]. It would be quite interesting if this simple bottom–up method could allow the development of GODs with different fluorescence peaks (or colors). However, it was found very difficult to prepare GODs with emission wavelengths other than 460nm by tuning pyrolysis degree. Under low carbonization, GODs (<15nm in size and with blue luminescence) were obtained, while under high carbonization, the large-sized GO nanomaterials with much lower luminescence activity were produced (Fig. 6). Secondly, the GQDs show a well-defined absorption band at 362nm with a narrow full width at half maximum of 66nm (it is should be noted here, CA exhibits only UV absorption below 250nm, Fig. 5), which further confirms that the sp2 clusters contained in GQDs should be uniform in size. Moreover the wavelength of the absorption peak of GQDs is almost the same as that of the excitation peak of GQDs (Fig. 6), implying that little non-emitting absorption has been produced in the GQDs. In contrast, the GO exhibits a broad UV–Vis absorption below 600nm without any obvious peak, suggesting that those sp2 clusters contained in GO is not uniform in size. Thirdly, although both GQDs and GO have their maximum PL quantum yields (PLQYs) at emission wavelength of 460nm, the GQDs show much stronger luminescence than the GO under excitation of 365nm light. The PLQYs of GQDs and GO at 365nm were calculated to be about 9.0% and 2.2%, respectively (selecting quinine sulfate as the standard). As well known, CLNMs without surface passivation usually have low PLQY, and the surface passivation will improve their PLQY obviously [22]. The relative high PLQY implies that the GQDs should be well surface-passivated, most likely by the incompletely carbonized CA. The GO exhibits a much lower PLQY than the GQDs, mostly due to two reasons: (1) the fully carbonization makes the GOD poorly passivated at its surfaces; (2) the non-emitting background absorption affects the PLQY calculation of GO. Fourthly, PL intensity and UV absorption of GQDs keep unchanged after adding a strong reductant, NaBH4. However, adding NaBH4 into the GO will not only reduce the UV absorption (Fig. 7
                     ) but also increase the PL intensity (Fig. 8
                     ), and thus improve the PLQY of GO from 2.2% to 3.9%. As mentioned above, sp2 clusters contained in the GO may be isolated within the sp3 C–O matrix (including C–O–C, COOH and C–OH). The reduction of GO by NaBH4 may remove some oxygen atoms from the sp3 C–O matrix. The removal of oxygen may on one hand decrease the non-emitting background absorption, and on the other hand lead to the formation of new isolated small sp2 domains consisting of a few repeating units. The new formed sp2 domains may have similar size distribution and surface states to those sp2 domains contained in the GO before reduction. Therefore, the reduction can increase the PL intensity of GO, but has nearly no effect on the PL wavelength. However, the sp2 clusters contained in the GQDs should be isolated within the incompletely carbonized CA. Therefore, the NaBH4 has no effect on the optical properties of GQDs.
